<dl id="n12139j"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12139j">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12139j"> 139(j)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> S.P.&apos;s monk ~</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Brendan is but the latest and definitely Christian example of a genre of story-telling which had already flourished for centuries in Ireland, when it seemed good to an unknown writer to dress the old half-pagan marvels in orthodox <mark>monkish</mark> garb, and thus start them afresh on their triumphal march through the literature of the world. <small> William James Perry, <a name="ORMR" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#ORMR"><cite title="source">Origin of Magic and Religion</cite></a> (1923) 82</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
